<p>Delmarva Power serves as the primary utility provider for most of Delaware, offering net metering programs that allow solar panel owners to sell excess electricity back to the grid at retail rates. This arrangement, combined with Delaware's commitment to renewable energy through various state incentives, creates a favorable environment for residential solar installations. The state's relatively small size and coastal location provide consistent weather patterns that make energy consumption predictable, allowing homeowners to accurately calculate potential savings from both solar panels and high-efficiency HVAC systems.</p>

<p>The synergy between solar panels and modern HVAC systems in Delaware is particularly compelling, as peak solar production typically coincides with peak cooling demands during summer months. This natural alignment allows homeowners to power their air conditioning systems directly with solar energy during the day, maximizing the value of their solar investment while maintaining comfortable indoor temperatures year-round.</p>

<h2>Solar Panels in Delaware</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Delaware's solar resource potential is robust despite its small geographical footprint, with the state receiving approximately 4.5 peak sun hours per day on average throughout the year. This solar irradiance level places Delaware in a favorable position compared to many northeastern states, with seasonal variations ranging from about 3.2 hours in December to 5.8 hours in June. The state's relatively flat terrain and coastal location minimize shading obstacles while providing consistent atmospheric conditions that support reliable solar energy production.</p>

<p>A typical residential solar installation in Delaware can generate between 1,100 to 1,400 kilowatt-hours per installed kilowatt annually, depending on system orientation, tilt angle, and local shading conditions. South-facing installations with optimal tilt angles of 30-40 degrees perform best, though east and west-facing arrays can still achieve 85-90% of optimal production. Delaware's net metering policy allows excess solar production to be credited at full retail value, making even slightly sub-optimal installations economically viable for most homeowners.</p>

